properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Unseasonably warm temperatures and high humidity expected for much of this week. Time span: tonight, Wednesday, Thursday and potentially into Friday. Maximum temperatures: Reaching or exceeding 30 degrees Celsius. Locations: New Brunswick (cooler temperatures for coastal communities). Remarks: Temperatures are expected to reach, or exceed, 30 degrees in parts of the province Wednesday, Thursday and into Friday. Humidex values are expected to reach the mid to high 30s. A cold front will bring a return to seasonable temperatures for the start of the weekend. A heat warning has been issued for portions of northwestern and central New Brunswick. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.
Expires: 2020-05-27T17:05:16-00:00

properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Smoke from a forest fire near Sabbies River is causing a reduction in air quality due to smoke in its vicinity and areas downwind to the east and northeast. Locations: Sabbies River to Rogersville and vicinity. Satellite imagery this morning showed smoke stretching eastward over an area roughly between Richibucto and Miramichi all the way to the coast. Short range wind forecast: Southwesterly 20 to 40 km/h diminishing this evening. On Wednesday, winds are forecast to be 10 to 20 km/h and variable in direction. Remarks: The forest fire is still out of control this afternoon and is covering an estimated area of 350 hectares as reported by New Brunswick Natural resources and Energy Development. More information will be provided as it becomes available. ### Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
Expires: 2020-05-27T14:59:16-00:00

properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Humidex values reaching 33 are expected for the next day. A period of very warm and humid weather is expected. Time span: Wednesday and Thursday, possibly into Friday. Maximum temperature Wednesday: 32 degrees C (Humidex 37) Minimum temperature Wednesday night: 17 degrees C Maximum temperature Thursday: 32 degrees C (Humidex 38) Locations: northwestern New Brunswick. Remarks: Cooler conditions will occur this weekend. ### Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of dangerous thunderstorms that may be capable of producing damaging wind gusts, large hail and heavy rain. A cold front tracking through the southern Prairies this evening is triggering thunderstorms some of which could become severe. Watches could be expanded later this evening as the cold front moves into central Saskatchewan. ### Very strong wind gusts can damage buildings, down trees and blow large vehicles off the road. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Ice build-up due to freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing rain is expected tonight and tomorrow near Collins Bay. Rain will transition to freezing rain through the night as surfaces cool to below freezing. The freezing rain is expected transition to snow by Wednesday afternoon. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
Expires: 2020-05-27T19:29:23-00:00
